[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-vermont/11th-united-states-congress] The **11th United States Congress** was a meeting of the legislative branch of the United States federal government, consisting of the United States Senate and the United States House of Representatives.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-vermont/11th-united-states-congress] It met in Washington, D.C., from March 4, 1809, to March 4, 1811, during the first two years of James Madison's presidency.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-vermont/11th-united-states-congress] The apportionment of seats in the House of Representatives was based on the 1800 United States census.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-vermont/11th-united-states-congress] Both chambers had a Democratic-Republican majority.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-vermont/11th-united-states-congress] The count below identifies party affiliations at the beginning of the first session of this congress.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-vermont/11th-united-states-congress] Changes resulting from subsequent replacements are shown below in the "Changes in membership" section.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-vermont/11th-united-states-congress] This list is arranged by chamber, then by state.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-vermont/11th-united-states-congress] Senators are listed by class, and representatives are listed by district.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-vermont/11th-united-states-congress] Senators were elected by the state legislatures every two years, with one-third beginning new six-year terms with each Congress.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-vermont/11th-united-states-congress] Preceding the names in the list below are Senate class numbers, which indicate the cycle of their election.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-vermont/11th-united-states-congress] In this Congress, Class 1 meant their term began with this Congress, requiring re-election in 1814; Class 2 meant their term ended with this Congress, requiring re-election in 1810; and Class 3 meant their term began in the last Congress, requiring re-election in 1812.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-vermont/11th-united-states-congress] The names of representatives are preceded by their districts.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-vermont/11th-united-states-congress] The count below reflects changes from the beginning of the first session of this Congress.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-vermont/11th-united-states-congress] There were 8 resignations, 2 deaths, 1 interim appointment, and 1 vacancy from before this Congress.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-vermont/11th-united-states-congress] Of the voting members, there were 12 resignations, 1 death, and 1 change due to a contested election.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-vermont/11th-united-states-congress] Lists of committees and their party leaders.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-vermont/1780-vermont-republic-gubernatorial-election] The **1780 Vermont Republic gubernatorial election** took place on September 5, 1780.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-vermont/1780-vermont-republic-gubernatorial-election] It resulted in the re-election of Thomas Chittenden to a one-year term.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-vermont/1780-vermont-republic-gubernatorial-election] The Vermont General Assembly met in Bennington on October 12.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-vermont/1780-vermont-republic-gubernatorial-election] The Vermont House of Representatives appointed a committee to examine the votes of the freemen of Vermont for governor, lieutenant governor, treasurer, and members of the governor's council.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-vermont/1780-vermont-republic-gubernatorial-election] Thomas Chittenden was re-elected governor.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-vermont/1780-vermont-republic-gubernatorial-election] Benjamin Carpenter was re-elected lieutenant governor, and Ira Allen was re-elected as treasurer.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-vermont/1780-vermont-republic-gubernatorial-election] The names of candidates and balloting totals were not recorded.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-vermont/1781-vermont-republic-gubernatorial-election] The **1781 Vermont Republic gubernatorial election** took place on September 4, 1781.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-vermont/1781-vermont-republic-gubernatorial-election] The Vermont General Assembly met in Charlestown, New Hampshire on October 12.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-vermont/1781-vermont-republic-gubernatorial-election] The meeting site was chosen as part of a short-lived effort to create a union of Vermont with 17 Connecticut River Valley towns of New Hampshire.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-vermont/1781-vermont-republic-gubernatorial-election] The Vermont House of Representatives appointed a committee to examine the votes of the freemen of Vermont for governor, lieutenant governor, treasurer, and governor's council members.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-vermont/1781-vermont-republic-gubernatorial-election] The popular vote indicated that no candidate for lieutenant governor had received a majority.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-vermont/1781-vermont-republic-gubernatorial-election] In keeping with the Vermont Constitution, the choice fell to the Vermont General Assembly, which chose Elisha Payne, a New Hampshire resident who supported the union of New Hampshire's western towns with Vermont.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-vermont/1782-vermont-republic-gubernatorial-election] The **1782 Vermont Republic gubernatorial election** took place on September 3, 1782.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-vermont/1782-vermont-republic-gubernatorial-election] The Vermont General Assembly met in Manchester on October 10.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-vermont/1782-vermont-republic-gubernatorial-election] Thomas Chittenden was re-elected to a one-year term as governor.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-vermont/1782-vermont-republic-gubernatorial-election] In keeping with the Vermont Constitution, the choice fell to the Vermont General Assembly, which chose Paul Spooner for a one-year term.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-vermont/1782-vermont-republic-gubernatorial-election] Ira Allen was re-elected to a one-year term as treasurer.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-vermont/1783-vermont-republic-gubernatorial-election] The **1783 Vermont Republic gubernatorial election** took place on September 2, 1783.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-vermont/1783-vermont-republic-gubernatorial-election] The Vermont General Assembly met in Westminster on October 9.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-vermont/1783-vermont-republic-gubernatorial-election] In the election for lieutenant governor, Paul Spooner was re-elected to a second one-year term.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-vermont/1783-vermont-republic-gubernatorial-election] In addition, Ira Allen was re-elected to a one-year term as treasurer.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-vermont/1784-vermont-republic-gubernatorial-election] The **1784 Vermont Republic gubernatorial election** took place on September 7, 1784.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-vermont/1784-vermont-republic-gubernatorial-election] The Vermont General Assembly met in Rutland on October 14.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-vermont/1784-vermont-republic-gubernatorial-election] In the race for governor, Thomas Chittenden was re-elected to a one-year term.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-vermont/1784-vermont-republic-gubernatorial-election] In the election for lieutenant governor, Paul Spooner was chosen for a third one-year term.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-vermont/1784-vermont-republic-gubernatorial-election] No candidate for treasurer obtained a majority.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-vermont/1784-vermont-republic-gubernatorial-election] In accordance with the Vermont Constitution, the Vermont General Assembly was required to make a selection.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-vermont/1784-vermont-republic-gubernatorial-election] On October 15, the Assembly (Vermont House of Representatives, governor, and governor's council) re-elected Ira Allen to a one-year term as treasurer.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-vermont/1785-vermont-republic-gubernatorial-election] The **1785 Vermont Republic gubernatorial election** took place on September 6, 1785.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-vermont/1785-vermont-republic-gubernatorial-election] The Vermont General Assembly met in Windsor on October 13.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-vermont/1785-vermont-republic-gubernatorial-election] In the race for governor, Thomas Chittenden was re-elected to a one-year term, his eighth.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-vermont/1785-vermont-republic-gubernatorial-election] In the election for lieutenant governor, Paul Spooner was chosen for a fourth one-year term.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-vermont/1785-vermont-republic-gubernatorial-election] On October 14, the Assembly (Vermont House of Representatives, governor, and governor's council) re-elected Ira Allen to his eighth one-year term as treasurer.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-vermont/1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-vermont] Following the September 1808 election for delegates to represent Vermont in the 11th United States Congress, two of its four districts had failed to choose representatives.
[src:1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-vermont/1808-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-vermont] A second ballot was held in December, giving Vermont a total of three Federalist representatives and one Democratic-Republican.
